Privileges :-
-----------------

  => privileges means permissions
  => privileges are 2 types 

 1  system privileges
 2  object privileges
 
 SYSTEM PRIVILEGES :-
 -----------------------------------

 => permissions on db are called system privileges
 => system privileges are grantetd by DBA using GRANT command

 Ex :- 
 
 SYSTEM :-
 ----------------

   SQL>GRANT CREATE SESSION TO NARESH ; 
   SQL>GRANT CREATE TABLE TO NARESH ; 

    OR

 SQL>GRANT CREATE SESSION , CREATE TABLE TO NARESH ; 

   OR

 SQL>GRANT CONNECT,RESOURCE TO NARESH ;

    CONNECT => CREATE SESSION
    RESOURCE => CREATE TABLE

  Object Privileges :- 
  ===============

   => permissions on table are called object privileges 
   => object  privileges are granted by owner of that object using GRANT command
 
Ex :- 

  => grant all permissions on emp table to naresh ?
    
  BATCH5253 :-
  ------------------

  SQL>GRANT ALL ON EMP TO NARESH ; 

 NARESH :- 
 ----------------

  SQL>SELECT * FROM BATCHT5253.EMP ;

  SQL>UPDATE BATCH5253.EMP SET SAL = 1000 WHERE EMPNO = 7369 ;
  
   note :- changes made by naresh are visible to batch5253 after commit

 Granting specific privileges :-
 -------------------------------------- 

 SQL> GRANT SELECT,INSERT,UPDATE ON DEPT TO NARESH ; 


 NARESH :-
 ----------------

 SQL>DELETE FROM BATCH5253.DEPT WHERE DEPTNO = 40 ;  => ERROR

 REVOKE command :- 
 ----------------------------

 => command used to take back permissions from users 

 Ex :- 

 SQL>REVOKE ALL ON EMP FROM NARESH ; 

 DB Objects :- 
 ------------------

 1  TABLES
 2  VIEWS
 3  SYNONYMS
 4  MATERIALIZED VIEWS
 5  SEQUENCES
 6  INDEXES 

  VIEWS :-  
  ------------

  => a  view is a subset of a table  i.e. part of a table.

  => a  view is a virtual table because it doesn't store data and doesn't occupy memory
       and it always derives data from table.
  
   => a view is a representation of a query
     
  => views are created 

    1 to provide security
    2 to reduce complexity
 
 => views are 2 types 

 1  simple views 
 2  complex views

 Simple views :- 
 ------------------------

  => if views created on single table then it is called simple view

   CREATE VIEW <NAME>
   AS  
   SELECT statement ;
 
Granting permission to create view :-
------------------------------------------------

 SYSTEM :-
 ---------------

  GRANT CREATE VIEW TO BATCH54;

Ex :-

BATCH54 :-
----------------------

  CREATE VIEW V1
  AS
  SELECT empno,ename,job,hiredate,deptno FROM emp ;
 
 => oracle creates view V1 and stores query but not query output 

    SELECT * FROM V1 ; 
 
 => when above query send to oracle then it executes the query as follows 

   SELECT * FROM (SELECT empno,ename,job,hiredate,deptno FROM emp) ;
 
 Granting permissions on view to user :-
 ------------------------------------------------------ 
 
   GRANT ALL ON V1 TO NARESH ; 

 NARESH :-
-----------------

  SQL>SELECT * FROM BATCH54.V1 ; 
  SQL>UPDATE BATCH54.V1 SET JOB='MANAGER' WHERE EMPNO = 7369;
  SQL>INSERT INTO BATCH54.V1 VALUES(888,'KKK','CLERK',SYSDATE,10);

 note :- 

  => changes made by naresh are visible to batch54 after commit.

  ROW LEVEL SECURITY :- 
  -------------------------------------

  CREATE VIEW V2 
  AS
 SELECT empno,ename,job,hiredate,deptno 
 FROM emp 
 WHERE deptno = 20 ; 

 GRANT ALL ON V2 TO NARESH ;

 NARESH :-
 ----------------
 
 SQL>SELECT * FROM BATCH54.V2 ; 
 
 SQL>INSERT INTO BATCH54.V2 VALUES(777,'BBB','clerk',sysdate,30);

  above insert command is executed successfully even though it is violating where cond

 WITH CHECK OPTION :-
 ------------------------------------

  => if view created with  "  WITH CHECK OPTION " then  any dml command through view
       violates where cond then that dml is not accepted.

   CREATE VIEW V3 
  AS
  SELECT empno,ename,job,hiredate,deptno 
  FROM emp 
  WHERE deptno = 20  
  WITH CHECK OPTION ; 

 GRANT ALL ON V3 TO NARESH ;

 NARESH :-
 ----------------
 
 INSERT INTO BATCH54.V3 VALUES(666,'HHH','clerk',sysdate,30);  => ERROR

 Complex views :-
 --------------------------

 => a view said to be complex view 

  1 if based on multiple tables (joins)
  2 if query contains 
                 group by clause
                 distinct clause
                 aggregate operations
                 set operations
                 sub-queries 

   => views reduces complexity i.e. with the help of views complex queries 
        can be converted into  simple queries.
 
 Ex 1 :- 

   CREATE VIEW CV1
   AS
   SELECT e.empno,e.ename,e.sal,
                  d.deptno,d.dname,d.loc
    FROM emp e INNER JOIN dept d
    ON e.deptno = d.deptno ; 
 

    after creating view whenever user wants data from emp & dept tables then instead of
    writing join query write the simple query as follows 
 
             SELECT * FROM CV1 ; 

Ex 2  :- 

  CREATE VIEW CV2
  AS
  SELECT job,MIN(sal) as minsal,
                       MAX(sal) as maxsal,
                       SUM(sal) as totsal,
                       AVG(sal) as avgsal,
                       COUNT(*) as cnt
   FROM emp 
   GROUP BY job ; 

   after creating view whenever we want job wise summary then execute the following simple query

    SELECT * FROM CV2; 

 => difference between simple and complex views ?

	simple				complex 

 1  based on single table			based on multiple tables 

 2  query performs simple operations		query performs  complex operations
					like  joins,group by and aggregate etc

 3   always updatable (allows dmls)		not updatable (doesn't allow dmls)
	

user_views :-
--------------------

  => it is a system table that stores information about views created by user

   => list of views created by user ?

      SELECT VIEW_NAME FROM USER_VIEWS ;

   => query associated with view v1 ?

      SELECT TEXT FROM USER_VIEWS WHERE VIEW_NAME='V1' ; 

Droping view :-
---------------------

  DROP VIEW V1 ; 

=> if we drop table what about views created on table ?

 ANS :-  views are not dropped but cannot be queried 

 
  synonyms :-
  ==========

  => a synonym is another name or alternative name for a table/view

  => if tablename is lengthy then we can give a simple and short name to the table
       called synonym and after creating synonym instead of using table name we can 
        use synonym name in SELECT / INSERT / UPDATE / DELETE queries.

           CREATE SYNONYM <name> FOR <tabname>

  Granting permission to create synonym :-
  ---------------------------------------------------------

   SYSTEM :-
   -----------------
 
  SQL>GRANT CREATE SYNONYM TO BATCH54 ;

 Ex :- 

 SQL>CREATE SYNONYM E FOR EMP ;

 after creating synonym instead of using table name use synonym name 

  SQL>SELECT * FROM E ;
  SQL>UPDATE E SET COMM=500 WHERE EMPNO=7369;
  


